e paths to the future. The third book in the Humanities to the Rescue series, the volume examines both lived and imagined utopian communities from an interdisciplinary perspective. While attentive to the troubled and troubling elements of different spaces and collectives, Utopian Imaginings remains premised in hope, culminating in a series of inspiring exemplars of the utopian potential of the college classroom today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 4aAmerican Studies : American Studies. 4aCultural Studies : Cultural Studies. 4aGender and Sexuality : Feminist. 4aHistory : History. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Religion. 7aHISTORY / United States / 19th Century.2bisacsh1 aButera, Anta C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aButler, Francis J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCampbell, Katelyn M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDorsey, Jennifer Hull, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aErtorer, Secil E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMuller, Dalia Antonia Caraballo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOlson, Alix, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPrince, Alexandra Leah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReitsma, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSegol, Marla, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShanahan, Dan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWolcott, Victoria V., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWolcott, Victoria W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aZamzlin, Alex, econ